# Doctrine Entity Pattern

Doctrine entities in this project are domain aggregates and should be modeled with aggregate discipline.

## Rules

- Put invariants in constructors, named constructors, or explicit aggregate methods.
- Prefer value objects over primitive obsession.
- Use enums for closed sets.
- Record domain events inside aggregates, dispatch them outside.
- Use ids across aggregate boundaries unless a real object association is required.
- Add database foreign keys in migrations even when aggregate references are stored as scalar ids.

## Avoid

- generic setter-driven models for meaningful transitions
- bidirectional associations by default
- controllers mutating entities directly
- leaking ORM concerns into application flow

## Persistence Rules

- keep migration schema aligned with aggregate fields
- if lifecycle timestamps/statuses are added in entity, update migration accordingly
- use repository queries for overlap/existence checks that require DB access
- use Doctrine aggregate repositories primarily on the write side
- prefer DBAL/raw SQL or dedicated read repositories on the query side when returning flat DTOs
